  <static seed="1573" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations1.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{-5}{x}} = {-5} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{1\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{x}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{-5}{x}} \amp = {-5} \\
   {\frac{-5}{x}} \cdot x \amp = {-5} \cdot x \\
   -5 \amp = -5x \\
   \frac{-5}{-5} \amp = \frac{-5 x}{-5} \\
   1 \amp = x \\
   x \amp = 1
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>x \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>x = 1</m>.</p>
</solution>
